* The subtle art of charging more: January is a popular time for retail pri=
ce increases=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s right after the holidays, many brands end=
 their fiscal years after January, and price hikes have time to breathe bef=
ore Valentine=E2=80=99s Day, Mother=E2=80=99s Day, and spring shopping seas=
ons. The challenge now is that the luxury consumer is ultra-sensitive to pr=
ice hikes, especially noticeable ones.=C2=A0

And yet, there=E2=80=99s always a way. After discussing this year=E2=80=99s
inflation outlook on a recent episode of Fashion People, Lauren and I heard=
 from listeners about luxury=E2=80=99s favorite psychological trick, which =
already appears to be in play: =E2=80=9Ccreeping inflation,=E2=80=9D or the=
 practice of raising prices in increments so tiny that consumers hardly not=
ice.

Pol=C3=A8ne=E2=80=94a French handbag line that has minimal designs that are=
 either logo-free or feature the increasingly derided gold-stamped emblem w=
e=E2=80=99ve come to expect from brands like A.P.C. and Mansur
Gavriel=E2=80=94increased prices on January 6, citing higher raw material a=
nd manufacturing costs. The hikes are between 5 and 8 percent=E2=80=94prett=
y small, but they add up, and eagle-eyed customers with long memories can o=
ften recall when a favorite style was, say, 30 percent less expensive. Most=
, however, barely notice. And that=E2=80=99s what brands are banking on. (A=
lthough it seems that, in this case, Pol=C3=A8ne is communicating the hike =
as a marketing tactic and flaunting their transparency.)=C2=A0

Relatedly,
I=E2=80=99ve been hearing that ambitious sales associates at Tiffany=E2=80=
=99s have been calling their best customers to entreat them to come in and =
shop before prices go up this week. Herm=C3=A8s is also raising prices for =
its bags, but holding the increases below 10 percent. (Herm=C3=A8s is fairl=
y judicious about price increases=E2=80=94as everyone who works in this ind=
ustry knows, the bags could be far more expensive and would still sell.) Bu=
t I=E2=80=99m hearing that brands with less stellar reputations are tweakin=
g, too, all the
way up to 10 percent, which feels like the most you can get away with these=
