px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It=E2=80=99s been a hectic start to the ye=
ar for the C.E.O.s of publicly
traded beauty concerns. Over at The Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies, <strong>St=
=C3=A9phane de La Faverie</strong> is wrapping up his first week atop the b=
usiness, kicking off what=E2=80=99s almost certain to be a <em>chaotic </em=
>first few months=E2=80=94or as it=E2=80=99s being referred to within the w=
alls of the GM Building, a =E2=80=9Csprint.=E2=80=9D De La Faverie is alrea=
dy bracing for a significant round of layoffs through February, a continuat=
ion of the vaguely Orwellian =E2=80=9CProfit Recovery and Growth Plan=E2=80=
=9D that began
implementation last year. But there are a slew of promotions coming, too, n=
ot least of which is the backfilling of de La Faverie=E2=80=99s old executi=
ve group president gig, a coveted role that once belonged to <strong>John D=
emsey</strong>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Unfortunately=E2=80=94<em>especia=
lly</em> for internal brand leads with big dreams=E2=80=94I=E2=80=99m heari=
ng this role could be eliminated entirely. But de La Faverie=E2=80=99s asce=
nsion may yet open
up a new lane for <strong>Jane Hudis</strong>, his former executive counter=
part, who could get the biggest promotion of all: head of <em>all</em> bran=
ds. This would essentially elevate Hudis to ELC=E2=80=99s No. 2, and give h=
er control of Lauder=E2=80=99s entire portfolio=E2=80=94fully tucking her i=
n, despite the fact that she didn=E2=80=99t get the top job.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">Meanwhile, another big beauty C.E.O. is out: On Monday, Ulta
Beauty, which operates around 1,400 stores in the U.S. and is known for its=
 sweeping assortment of prestige <em>and</em> drugstore beauty items, abrup=
tly announced that C.E.O.<strong> David Kimbell</strong> would =E2=80=9Cret=
ire=E2=80=9D <em>effective immediately</em>, and that <strong>Kecia Steelma=
n</strong>, current president and C.O.O., would replace him. Ulta enjoyed a=
 better-than-expected holiday season, but shares had dipped nearly 14 perce=
nt over the last 12 months, and Kimbell wasn=E2=80=99t as successful at
engineering a turnaround as many had hoped. Indeed, the market had begun to=
 suspect this change might be coming a year ago, when Steelman had =E2=80=
=9Cpresident=E2=80=9D added to her title (the same sequence that preceded K=
imbell=E2=80=99s elevation).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99m told tha=
t =E2=80=9Cnothing scandalous=E2=80=9D led to Kimbell=E2=80=99s exit, which=
 follows the retirement of <strong>Monica Arnaudo</strong>, the company=E2=
=80=99s chief merchandising officer, about six
weeks ago. Sure, Kimbell, who=E2=80=99s been C.E.O. since 2021, may have fo=
mented a minor panic in the industry last summer when Ulta lowered its full=
-year outlook. But this was nothing like the code red Lauder situation, whe=
re the stock=E2=80=99s been plunging for the past three years. Instead, an =
insider pointed to another dynamic at play. Several years ago, before 11-ye=
ar-olds started pillaging their local Sephoras, Ulta was the go-to place fo=
r Kylie Lip Kits, Morphe eye shadow palettes, and Lime Crime
(remember them?). In other words, Kimbell=E2=80=99s exit was largely relate=
d to <em>where</em> teenagers are now choosing to buy overpriced skincare t=
hey don=E2=80=99t even need.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It also surely didn=E2=
=80=99t help that Sephora=E2=80=99s shop-in-shops at Kohl=E2=80=99s=E2=80=
=94they expect to be in all 1,200 locations by the end of this year=E2=80=
=94have expanded <em>much </em>faster than Ulta Beauty=E2=80=99s at Target.=
 (Ulta=E2=80=99s shop-in-shops currently number about 500,
even though Target had originally detailed plans for 800 locations.) =E2=80=
=9CTarget Ulta is not working,=E2=80=9D is how another insider bluntly put =
it. But <em>another</em> person with knowledge of Ulta=E2=80=99s business p=
rovided a more nuanced explanation: that the partnership has been hamstrung=
 by a clause in the deal regarding the proximity of shop-in-shops to stand-=
alone Ulta stores. Ulta, it turns out, is worried about the potential canni=
balization of sales in its existing doors. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s definitely=
 not being
communicated as a failure,=E2=80=9D this person added. (A spokesperson for =
Ulta didn=E2=80=99t respond to a request for comment.)</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Still, there=E2=80=
=99s a certain lopsidedness to the partnership. Target isn=E2=80=99t riskin=
g much beyond some dedicated store space, while gaining an assortment of hi=
gher-end, higher-yield brands it doesn=E2=80=99t already carry. (Sale margi=
ns are about 50 percent for the shop-in-shops, compared to the typical 45 p=
ercent-ish spread
on Target beauty.) Ulta, according to one of the people with knowledge of i=
ts business, only gets a mid-single-digit royalty on any sale registered at=
 the shop-in-shop. =E2=80=9CTarget beauty is getting a halo effect from Ult=
a, and Target beauty is doing well,=E2=80=9D this person explained. =E2=80=
=9CWhich is far more important than Target Ulta.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
