149a" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;"><em>Blake vs. Bald=
oni, Round 2</em></a>.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I thought that sales for Blake =
Brown might rebound after the filing of her double-barreled lawsuit against=
 Baldoni and a well-orchestrated <em>New York Times</em> piece. But I may h=
ave spoken too soon. On New Year=E2=80=99s Eve, 10 days after Lively filed =
her
suit, Baldoni filed a suit of his own against Lively and the <em>Times</em>=
 that rebutted many of Lively=E2=80=99s allegations, offering a counterfact=
ual he-said, she-said accounting of events. I don=E2=80=99t know what=E2=80=
=99s true and what=E2=80=99s not=E2=80=93=E2=80=93besides all parties comin=
g off like childish egomaniacs, hell-bent on out-smearing each other=E2=80=
=93=E2=80=93but unfortunately for Lively, the support and positive sentimen=
t appears to have been short-lived. This drama is increasingly messy, and m=
ess is never good for sales. =E2=80=9CThey got a
ton of returns,=E2=80=9D said a person close to Target=E2=80=99s business. =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m assuming it will continue to get worse.=E2=80=9D (It=
=E2=80=99s worth noting that Target=E2=80=99s overall beauty business is <e=
m>very </em>strong, and the retailer reported in November that =E2=80=9Cin =
terms of the category performance, sales and market share gains were strong=
est in beauty again this quarter.=E2=80=9D)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99v=
e also heard that Target=E2=80=99s team is fielding =E2=80=9Cemotional=E2=
=80=9D
negative feedback about Blake Brown, feedback that mostly pertains to =E2=
=80=9CBlake=E2=80=99s personality=E2=80=9D as opposed to the products thems=
elves. (Whether it=E2=80=99s some sort of astroturf campaign, I=E2=80=99m n=
ot in a position to say.) Alas, Blake Brown was the biggest haircare launch=
 in Target history, with early numbers eclipsing some of the retailer=E2=80=
=99s most successful hair brands. In its first three and a half weeks, Blak=
e Brown=E2=80=99s sales came close to $5 million, and Target had projected =
<em>nine-figure sales</em> in the
first year. =E2=80=9CIt could be about a $40 million to $45 million brand, =
which is still fine, but it=E2=80=99s not going to be the $100 million-plus=
 brand anymore,=E2=80=9D the person close to Target=E2=80=99s business adde=
d. (Blake Brown declined to comment.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">What=E2=80=99s mo=
re, this is the <em>second</em> celebrity brand in about a year that hasn=
=E2=80=99t panned out as Target executives had hoped. I=E2=80=99ve heard th=
at Goop Beauty=E2=80=99s diffusion line
Good.Clean.Goop, which Target began selling in 2023, was in the =E2=80=9Cbo=
ttom 15=E2=80=9D products at Target that year, with sales just over $1 mill=
ion. While the products are not directly comparable, Blake Brown=E2=80=99s =
sales have eclipsed Good.Clean.Goop=E2=80=99s at Target locations <em>many =
</em>times over. This is partly due to apprehension over marketing Good.Cle=
